<p class="p2"><span class="s1">The third week of my REU is coming to a close.  Here's what I've worked on so far.
<p>
A sequence \(z_n \in \mathbb{D}\) is called <b>interpolating</b> if for every other sequence \(a_n \in \ell^{\infty}(\mathbb{D})\) (that means there exists some \(M > 0\) which is greater than the magnitudes of every element of the sequence), there is some bounded analytic function \(f \in H^{\infty}(\mathbb{D}\)
for which \(f(z_n) = a_n\) for all \(n\).  This seems like a pretty strict condition, but Carleson (see, e.g., Garnett, "Bounded Analytic Functions") showed that the following are equivalent: <ul>
<li>The sequence \(z_n\) is interpolating</li>
<li>\[\inf_n \prod_{m\neq n}\rho(z_n, z_m) > 0\]</li>
<li>\(\inf_{n, m} \rho(z_n, z_m) > 0\), and furthermore,\[\sum_{z_n \in S(I)} (1-z_n)\delta_{z_n} < C|I|,\] 
for all arcs \(I \subseteq \mathbb{T}\), where \(S(I) := \{re^{2 \pi i \theta} : e^{2 \pi i \theta} \in I, r \in (|I|, 1)\}\) is called a <b>Carleson square</b> and \(\delta_z\) is the unit point mass.
</li>
</ul>
where \(\rho\) is the pseudohyperbolic metric \(\rho(z, w) := \left|\frac{z-w}{z\overline{w} - 1}\right|\).  If you are familiar with the Blaschke map, you'll see this is the same thing.
</p>

My group is looking at the sequence \(z_n = (1-\frac{1}{n^p})e^{2 \pi i n \alpha}\) and examining the relationship between \(\alpha\) and \(p\) when \(z_n\) is interpolating. <br> <br>

So far we've found that \((z_n)\) is interpolating precisely when \(\alpha\) is Diophantine with exponent \(p\), that is, for all \(p, q \in \mathbb{Z}\) \[|p\alpha - q| \geq p^n.\]

<p> <i>Proof.</i>
First, we show that if \((z_n)\) is separated if and only if \(\alpha\) satisfies the Diophantine Condition.  Then we show that when the Diophantine Condition is satisfied, the Carleson square property is also satisfied.
</p>

<ol>
<li> If \((z_n)\) is separated then it satisfies the Diophantine Condition.  <details>
  <summary><b>Proof</b></summary>
  <p>Suppose \(a_n\) is separated by \(c\).  Then we will show that the condition (\(\alpha\) is Diophantine of exponent \(p\)) holds. 
<br>
Let \(r_n := 1 - \frac{1}{n^p}\).  Computation tells us \begin{align*}
    c < \rho\left(\left(1-\frac{1}{n^p}\right)e^{2 \pi i k\alpha}, 1 - \frac{1}{(n+k)^p}\right) &\leq \frac{|r_n - r_{n+k}| + r_{n+k}|1 - e^{2 \pi i \alpha k}|}{|1 - r_n r_{n+k}e^{2 \pi i k\alpha}|}\\
    &= \frac{\left|\frac{1}{(n+k)^p} - \frac{1}{n^p}\right| + r_{n+k}2|\sin(\pi \Vert \alpha k \Vert)|}{|1 - r_n r_{n+k}|}\\
    &\leq \frac{\left|\frac{1}{(n+k)^p} - \frac{1}{n^p}\right| + C\Vert \alpha k\Vert}{|\frac{1}{n^p}|}\\
    &= \left|1 - \frac{(n+k)^p}{n^p} + n^p C \Vert \alpha k \Vert \right|.
\end{align*}

Let \(n = mk\), and choose \(m\) such that \(1 - \left(\frac{m}{m+1}\right)^p < \frac{c}{2}\).  Using the computations above we see that
\begin{align*}
    \rho\left(\left(1-\frac{1}{n^p}\right)e^{2 \pi i k\alpha}, 1 - \frac{1}{(n+k)^p}\right)&<\left|1 - \frac{(n+k)^p}{n^p} + n^p C \Vert \alpha k \Vert \right| \\
    &= \left| 1 - \frac{(m+1)^p}{m^p} + m^pk^p C \Vert \alpha k \Vert \right|\\
    &< \frac{c}{2} + m^pk^p C\Vert \alpha k \Vert.
\end{align*}
Putting it all together gives \[\frac{1}{Cm^p}\left(c - \frac{c}{2}\right) < k^p \Vert \alpha k \Vert\] and we see that \[\inf_{k \in \mathbb{Z}^+}  k^p \Vert \alpha k \Vert> 0,\] which is precisely the Diophantine condition.</p>
</details></li>
<li> If the Diophantine condition holds, then \(a_n\) is separated. <details><summary><b>Proof</b></summary>
  <p>
\begin{align*}
    \rho\left(\left(1-\frac{1}{n^p}\right)e^{2 \pi i k\alpha}, 1 - \frac{1}{(n+k)^p}\right) 
    &= \frac{|(r_n - r_{n+k}) + r_{n+k}(1 - e^{2 \pi i \alpha k})|}{|1 - r_n r_{n+k}e^{2 \pi i k\alpha}|}\\
    &\geq \frac{|r_{n+k}(1 - e^{2 \pi i \alpha k})|}{|1 - r_n r_{n+k}e^{2 \pi i k\alpha}|}
\end{align*}

And as we can see, the denominator can be bounded above well
\begin{align*}
    \left| 1 - r_nr_{n+k}e^{2 \pi i k \alpha} \right|  &= \left|1 - e^{2 \pi i k\alpha} + \left(\frac{1}{(n+k)^p} + \frac{1}{n^p} - \frac{1}{(n+k)^pn^p} \right)e^{2 \pi i k \alpha} \right|\\
    &\leq |1 - e^{2 \pi i k\alpha}| +  \left|\frac{1}{(n+k)^p} + \frac{1}{n^p}- \frac{1}{(n+k)^pn^p} \right|\\
    &\leq |1 - e^{2 \pi i k\alpha}| +  \left|\frac{1}{(n+k)^p}r_{n} \right|\\
    &< |1 - e^{2 \pi i k\alpha}| +  \left| \frac{1}{k^p}r_{n+k} \right|
\end{align*}
since \(r_n < r_{n+k}\) while \(\frac{1}{a+b} < \frac{1}{a}\).  Finally, putting it all together and assuming the Diophantine condition, we see that
\begin{align*}
    \rho\left(\left(1-\frac{1}{n^p}\right)e^{2 \pi i k\alpha}, 1 - \frac{1}{(n+k)^p}\right)  &> \frac{r_{n+k}\left|(1 - e^{2 \pi i k \alpha})\right|}{|1 - e^{2 \pi i k\alpha}| +  \left| \frac{1}{k^p}r_{n+k} \right|} \\
    &= \frac{r_{n+k}}{1 + \left|\frac{\frac{1}{k^p} r_{n+k}}{|1 - e^{2 \pi i k\alpha}|} \right|}\\
    &> \frac{r_{n+k}}{1 + \left|\frac{\frac{1}{k^p} r_{n+k}}{\frac{C}{k^p}r_{n+k}} \right|}\\ 
    &= \frac{Cr_{n+k}}{C+1} > \frac{C}{2C+ 2} > 0.
\end{align*}
since \(r_{n+k} > \frac{1}{2}\).  (This makes sense because \(C\) is usually very small).</p> </details> </li>

<li> </li>
</ol>


